.SH NAME
Mooish::Base \- importer for Mooish classes
.SH SYNOPSIS
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&        # for classes
\&        use Mooish::Base;
\&
\&        # for roles
\&        use Mooish::Base \-role;
\&
\&        # create your class / role as usual
.Ve
.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This module is a shortcut that does roughly the same as calling these imports:
.PP
.Vb 4
\&        use Moo;
\&        use Mooish::AttributeBuilder;
\&        use Types::Common \-types;
\&        use namespace::autoclean;
\&
\&        # additional optional modules, if they are installed
.Ve
.PP
If a \f(CW\*(C`\-role\*(C'\fR flag is specified, then the module imports \f(CW\*(C`Moo::Role\*(C'\fR instead.
.PP
Environmental variables \f(CW\*(C`MOOISH_BASE_FLAVOUR\*(C'\fR and \f(CW\*(C`MOOISH_BASE_ROLE_FLAVOUR\*(C'\fR
can be used to modify class and role systems used. If not present, \f(CW\*(C`Moo\*(C'\fR and
\&\f(CW\*(C`Moo::Role\*(C'\fR will be used respectively. Make sure to introduce these variables
before first loading the module.
.PP
The purpose of this module is to make it easier to create classes based on
Moose family of modules. The choice of imported modules is meant to provide a
solid base for module development, but still be perfectly compatible at least
with Moose, Mouse and Moo.
.SS "Extra modules or features loaded"
.IX Subsection "Extra modules or features loaded"
Depending on \f(CW\*(C`MOOISH_BASE_FLAVOUR\*(C'\fR some extra modules will be imported (if
installed). Only modules which \fBdo not change the behavior\fR will ever be
added to this list \- mostly modules which improve performance for free.
.PP
\&\f(CW\*(C`MOOISH_BASE_EXTRA_MODULES\*(C'\fR environmental variable can be declared to control
which extra modules should be used. It must contain a semicolon\-separated a
list of modules to be loaded, for example
\&\f(CW\*(C`MooX::TypeTiny;MooX::XSConstructor\*(C'\fR. It must be set prior to first loading
the module to take effect. Normally, it should not be needed, but may be a
helpful workaround if one of these modules contain a bug which causes the
resulting class to misbehave.
.PP
\fIMoo\fR
.IX Subsection "Moo"
.IP \(bu 4
MooX::TypeTiny
.Sp
This module speeds up Type::Tiny checks in Moo code.
.Sp
\&\fIminimum required version: 0.002002\fR
.IP \(bu 4
MooX::XSConstructor
.Sp
This module attempts to use Class::XSConstructor to speed up the constructor.
.Sp
\&\fBThis module is disabled by default\fR. XSConstructor modules are not stable
enough to be enabled by default. It can be enabled manually with
\&\f(CW\*(C`MOOISH_BASE_EXTRA_MODULES\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
\&\fIminimum required version: 0.003002\fR
.PP
\fIMoose\fR
.IX Subsection "Moose"
.IP \(bu 4
MooseX::XSConstructor
.Sp
This module attempts to use Class::XSConstructor to speed up the constructor.
.Sp
\&\fBThis module is disabled by default\fR. XSConstructor modules are not stable
enough to be enabled by default. It can be enabled manually with
\&\f(CW\*(C`MOOISH_BASE_EXTRA_MODULES\*(C'\fR.
.Sp
\&\fIminimum required version: 0.001002\fR
.IP \(bu 4
MooseX::XSAccessor
.Sp
This module attempts to use Class::XSAccessor to speed up the accessors.
.Sp
\&\fIminimum required version: 0.010\fR
.IP \(bu 4
Hook::AfterRuntime
.Sp
Since the module attempts to deliver a unified API for each flavour of Moose,
Moose itself must be made immutable automatically after the class is built.
This is done with the help of this module. Mooish::Base will warn if this
module is not installed and Moose flavour is used.
.Sp
\&\fIminimum required version: 0.003\fR
.SS Debugging
.IX Subsection "Debugging"
Mooish::Base can be debugged by setting \f(CW$Mooish::Base::DEBUG\fR prior to
loading a class. This package variable should be set to a hash reference. If it
is, it will fill it up with keys for each loaded class or role. An example
debug code will look like that:
.PP
.Vb 4
\&        BEGIN {
\&                require Mooish::Base;
\&                $Mooish::Base::DEBUG = {};
\&        }
\&
\&        package MyClass;
\&        use Mooish::Base;
\&
\&        use Data::Dumper;
\&        print Dumper($Mooish::Base::DEBUG);
.Ve
.PP
Example output:
.PP
.Vb 10
\&        $VAR1 = {
\&                \*(AqMyClass\*(Aq => {
\&                        \*(Aqclass_type\*(Aq => \*(AqMoo\*(Aq,
\&                        \*(Aqrole_type\*(Aq => \*(AqMoo::Role\*(Aq,
\&                        \*(Aqrole\*(Aq => !!0,
\&                        \*(Aqstandard\*(Aq => !!0
\&                        \*(Aqextra_modules\*(Aq => {
\&                                \*(AqMooX::TypeTiny\*(Aq => !!1,
\&                                \*(AqMooX::XSConstructor\*(Aq => !!0,
\&                                \*(AqHook::AfterRuntime\*(Aq => !!0,
\&                                \*(AqMooseX::XSConstructor\*(Aq => !!0,
\&                                \*(AqMooseX::XSAccessor\*(Aq => !!0
\&                        },
\&                }
\&        };
.Ve
.PP
If more classes are loaded then more keys will appear in the debug hash,
allowing to easily check what was loaded and where.
.SS "For module authors"
.IX Subsection "For module authors"
If you wish to use Mooish::Base in your module, please use it with \f(CW\*(C`\-standard\*(C'\fR
flag. This flag will prevent custom behavior from propagating into the module.
The idea is to have a solid base OO for module development while making sure
that it won\*(Aqt break when users add custom settings.
.PP
Currently, it will ensure that:
.IP \(bu 4
Mooish::AttributeBuilder will be imported with \f(CW\*(C`\-standard\*(C'\fR flag (no
user\-defined shortcuts). \fI(in effect since version 1.000)\fR
.IP \(bu 4
Moo and Moo::Role will be used regardless of the environment variables.
\&\fI(in effect since version 1.001)\fR
